onnects collecting—whether by individuals or institutions—to the professionalization of the historical profession, one which came to regard its progenitors with skepticism and disdain. The struggle to articulate the value of objects as historical evidence, then, lies at the heart both of academic history-writing and of the popular engagement with things.Ultimately, this book demonstrates that our current preoccupation with objects is far from novel and reflects a human need to reexperience the past as a physical presence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAntiquitiesxStudy and teaching. 0aMaterial culturexHistory. 4aArt History. 4aHistory.  aA History of the World in 100 Objects.  aAntiquities.  aCultural Histories of the Material World.  aCultural history material.  aCultural history.  aHistoriography Material culture.  aThe Hare with Amber Eyes.  aancient world.  aanthropologists.  aantiquarian history .  aantiquarianism.  aarchaeology .  aart history .  acuration studies .  aeurope historiography .  ahistoriography.  ahistory of objects .  amaterial Cultural history.  amaterial art history .  amaterial culture studies.  amaterial culture.  amuseum studies .  amuseumology .08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501708244?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501708244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501708244/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles